def plot_logscale(X, field):
    '''
    This function will plot the distribution of original data and log data.
    '''
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = [17, 4])
    plt.subplot(121)
    sns.kdeplot(X[field], label = field)
    plt.title('Kdeplot of {}'.format(field))
    plt.xlabel(field)
    
    plt.subplot(122)
    sns.kdeplot(np.log(X[field]), label = 'log {}'.format(field))
    plt.title('Kdeplot of Log {}'.format(field))
    plt.xlabel('Log {}'.format(field))

def plot_logpoint(X, field):
    '''
    This function will plot the points between input field and sale_price compare
    to log scale
    '''
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize = [17, 4])
    plt.subplot(121)
    sns.scatterplot(X[field], X.sale_price)
    plt.title('Scatterplot of {}'.format(field))
    plt.xlabel(field)
    
    plt.subplot(122)
    sns.scatterplot(np.log(X[field]), np.log(X.sale_price), label = 'log sale price')
    plt.title('Scatterplot of Log {}'.format(field))
    plt.xlabel('Log {}'.format(field))

def Normaltest(X):
    
    k2, p = stats.normaltest(X)
    alpha = 0.05
    
    if p < alpha:
        print('it can be rejected that the input is normal distribution')
    else:
        print('can not reject the input is normal distirbution')
        
    return('p value is: {:.3e}'.format(p))

Here I created a class named data_analysis. In this class, there are three function which will be used to analyse the data. The first function is the main function which called process. In this function, firstly, I add one new feature called nb_level, which is to define the level of price of neighborhood based on the average price. Adding this feature is because the sale_price has relationship to the neiborhood and group it may predict better. It will be process in the initilize part. Then I log scale the sale_price field. The reason is because this data is right skewed and it is hard for the model to predict long tail data. The comparasion of sale_price and log sale_price can be seen below, which shows the log sale_price is symmetric and easier to be predicted.

In [7]:
plot_logscale(sales, 'sale_price')

Secondly, from the pairplot in the begining, we can find in the row of lot_area, there is some outliers and the distribution is also right skewed. So I use log scale again to reduce the distance between outliers and normal points. It also can make it symmetric. These two reasons make it easier to predict sale price. The comparasion of scatter plot and kde plot can be seen below.

In [8]:
plot_logpoint(sales, 'lot_area')
plot_logscale(sales, 'lot_area')

Then, I try to remove the outliers based on sale_price. I created two outlier removing methods, the one is using 3$\delta$ thery of normal distriution. Another one is using Inter Quartile Range. When using 3$\delta$ theory, it is better to check whether the sample is follow normal distribution. Below is a normal distribution test.

From above test, we can not use normal distribution to remove the outlier. So it is better to use IQR to remove the outliers. below is the boxplot of sale_price.

We can find there are many points outside the maximum value(Q3 + 1.5IQR). However, after tried these two outlier detections, the results show that removing outlier can improve the RMSE of training data but it is useless for predict test data. The reason is that I have overfit the model and the outlier is not only appear in the training data but also in test data. So that I will not using outlier detection methods for this data. The results will be showed in supplemental notebook.

Then I devide the data into numeric data and categorical data. The categorical data is the string data after dummy process. In numeric data, I also devide them into normal data and ordered data. The ordered data is the number of rooms or garage cars. In process function, I also set a parameter called only_continuous which is used for whether scale only the numeric data or scale the whole data. When only_continuous is True, I use StandardScale process for normal data and log scale for ordered data, The reason is ordered data has smaller deviance than one and it is not good to scale it to one and scale categorical data make no sense and it will even make prediction worse. The standard deviation of each feature can be seen below.It should be noticed that I drop the variable year_sold. The reason is that it has too small deviation compare to other normal data and small correlation with sale price which will be discussed in the later part. These are all the preprocess procedures in the process function.

class data_analysis:
    '''
    This class has three functions. The first function is used to preprocess
    data and return the variable and label. The second function is used to 
    calculate the correlation between each feature and plot in a heat map. 
    The third function is used to plot the points between pc components 
    and sales price.
    '''
    
    def __init__(self, train, test):
        self.train = train.copy()
        self.test = test.copy()
        self.x = self.train.shape[0]
        self.y = self.test.shape[0]
        self.sales = pd.concat([self.train, self.test], axis=0)
        
        #using train data as reference
        low = self.train.groupby(['neighborhood']).mean().sale_price.sort_values(axis=0).index[0:10]
        median = self.train.groupby(['neighborhood']).mean().sale_price.sort_values(axis=0).index[10:18]
        high = self.train.groupby(['neighborhood']).mean().sale_price.sort_values(axis=0).index[18:24]
        #perfrom to the whole data
        self.sales['nb_level'] = self.sales.neighborhood
        self.sales.nb_level.replace(low, np.repeat('nb_low', 10), inplace = True)
        self.sales.nb_level.replace(median, np.repeat('nb_median', 8), inplace = True)
        self.sales.nb_level.replace(high, np.repeat('nb_high', 6), inplace = True)
        
        self.sales_scale = []
        self.numeric = []
        self.all_dummy = []
        self.sales_scale_numeric = []
        
    def process(self, only_continuous=True):
        '''
        This function is used to process the input data
        -----------------------------------------------
        Parameters:
            data: array
            
            only_continuous: (boolean, default True) 
                whether only sacle the sales price with continuous value.
            
        ----------------------------------------------
        Attributes:
            X: array
                data input
            
            y: array
                data output
        '''
        
        #from the pair plot, The sales price feild is right skewed, it is hard for 
        # model to predict long tail, so using log make it symetric
        self.sales.sale_price = np.log(self.sales.sale_price)
        
        #from the pair plot, we find there are outliers in lot_area field, so using
        #log to reduce the distance between outliers and normal points
        self.sales.lot_area = np.log(self.sales.lot_area)
        
        #store all the numeric data 
        self.numeric = self.sales[self.sales.describe().columns]
        
        #drop variable for the whole data
        drop_varibale = ['sale_price', 'year_sold']
        ordered_variable = ['full_bath', 'half_bath', 'bedroom', 'garage_cars']
        
        #dummy code
        self.sales_dummy = pd.get_dummies(self.sales).drop(drop_varibale, axis = 1)
        
        #get the column name of continuous data
        continuous_name = self.sales.describe().columns.drop(drop_varibale).drop(ordered_variable)
        
        #standardscale the data
        scaler = StandardScaler().fit(self.sales[0:self.x][continuous_name])
        self.sales_scale = self.sales_dummy.copy()
        
        #whether choose only continuous data to be scaled, transform data using
        #training parameter
        if only_continuous == True:
            self.sales_scale[continuous_name] = scaler.transform(self.sales_scale[continuous_name])
            self.sales_scale[ordered_variable] = np.log1p(self.sales_scale[ordered_variable])
        else:
            self.sales_scale[:] = scaler.transform(self.sales_dummy)
            
        #store the scaled numeric continuous variable
        self.sales_scale_numeric = self.sales_scale[0:self.x][continuous_name]
        
        y = self.sales.sale_price
        X = self.sales_scale
        train_x = X[0:self.x]
        test_x = X[self.x:self.x+self.y]
        train_y = y[0:self.x]
        test_y = y[self.x:self.x+self.y]
        
        return train_x, train_y, test_x, test_y
    
    def get_corr(self, plot=True):
        '''
        This function will return the correlation between each feature and plot
        the heatmap of corr matrix
        --------------------------------
        args:
            plot:(default True)
                whether to plot the heatmap
                
        note:
            in order to see the entire plot, it is better to use the matplotlib
            version of 3.1.0
        '''
        
        corr = np.round(self.numeric.corr(method='pearson'),4)
        
        if plot == True:
            fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 1)
            sns.heatmap(np.abs(corr), annot=True, fmt=".1f", linewidths=.5)
            plt.title('The Heat Map of Correlation between each Feature')
        
        return corr

Here I will discuss the year_sold feature. From the heatmap of all numeric data, we can find a stange thing which is in the second row and second column, the correlations are all almost zero. It means the feature year_sold is irrelevant to not only sale price but also other features. So it is better to remove year_sold feature. The result also shows that remove year_sold can reduce the total RMSE.

I have tried PCA to reduce the dimension and extract more useful information to improve prediction. However, it is not useful for this data. only first component has a good relationship with sale price, the other components is very messy. using PCA even make prediction worse. So I didn't use PCA for this data. The PCA discussion can be seen in supplemental notebook.

3. Model Fitting and Tuning¶

I have tried linear regression, Linear Lasso, Linear Redge, kernel ridge with laplacian, polynomial with degree 2, cosine and rbf kernels and SVR modeling methods for this data.The performance of lm, lasso, redge is similar because they are all based lienar regression and every $\beta$ is small, regularization does not have improvement. SVR is similar to kernel ridge, but SVR is trying to maximize the margin while kernel ridge trying to minimise the RSS. Because kernel ridge is faster than SVR and it performs better, so I reject the SVR. Kernel ridge with rbf kernel and polynomial kernel models have similiar performance, in order to test which kernel has more robust performance, I concatenate the training data and test data and use train_test_split to reorganize the training data and test. The result shows that polynomial kernel always perform better than rbf kernel. The reason may be that the polynomial kernel not only considers the similarities in the same dimension but also across dimensions. The results can be seen below and comparasion can be found in supplemental file.

The Kernel Ridge regression minimizes the penalized RSS with kernel trick. Firstly, from linear ridge regression, we can get $$\hat{w} = X^T(\lambda I_N + XX^T)^{-1}y$$ Where $XX^T$ can be replacing with Gram matrix K. $$\hat{w} = X^T(\lambda I_N + K)^{-1}y$$ Let's define $$\alpha = (\lambda I_N + K) ^ {-1}y$$ So that predictions have the form: $$\hat{y}^\star = X^T\alpha x^\star = \sum_{n=1}^{N}\alpha_nx_n^{T}x^\star$$ And we can use the kernel trick to replace the inner product $x_n^{T}x^\star$ $$\hat{y}^\star = \sum_{n=1}^N \alpha_nk(x_n^T,x^\star)$$ The kernel I used is polynomial with degree 2 and it has the form $$k(x,y) = (\gamma x^Ty + c_0)^2$$ In the later part, I will try to tune $\lambda$ and $\gamma$ to get the model with best performance. I leave the $c_0$ to be 1 because change $c_0$ cause overfit and make prediction worse.

In [17]:
def model_fit(m, X, y, alpha=None, gamma=None, plot = False):
    """Returns the root mean squared error of a fitted model based on provided X and y values.
    
    Args:
        m: sklearn model object
        X: model matrix to use for prediction
        y: outcome vector to use to calculating rmse and residuals
        plot: boolean value, should fit plots be shown 
    """
    
    #test the root mean square between y and y_hat    
    y_hat = m.predict(X)
    rmse = mean_squared_error(y, y_hat, squared=False)
    
    #test the root mean square between actual y and y hat
    actual_y_hat = np.exp(y_hat)
    actual_y = np.exp(y)
    actual_rmse = mean_squared_error(actual_y, actual_y_hat, squared=False)
    
    res = pd.DataFrame(
        data = {'y': y, 'y_hat': y_hat, 'resid': y - y_hat}
    )
    
    if plot:
        plt.figure(figsize=(12, 4))
        
        plt.subplot(121)
        sns.lineplot(x='x', y='y', color="grey", data =  pd.DataFrame(data={'x': [min(y),max(y)], 'y': [min(y),max(y)]}))
        sns.scatterplot(x='y', y='y_hat', data=res)
        if alpha == None and gamma == None:
            plt.title("Fit Plot\nrmse = %.4f\nactual rmse = %.4f\nFit Plot" % (rmse, actual_rmse))
        elif alpha != None and gamma == None:
            plt.title("alpha = %.5f\nrmse = %.4f\nactual rmse = %.4f\nFit Plot" % 
              (alpha, rmse, actual_rmse))
        elif alpha == None and gamma != None:
            plt.title("gamma = %.4f\nrmse = %.4f\nactual rmse = %.4f\nFit Plot" % 
              (gamma, rmse, actual_rmse))
        else:
            plt.title("alpha = %.5f gamma = %.4f\nrmse = %.4f\nactual rmse = %.4f\nFit Plot" % 
              (alpha, gamma, rmse, actual_rmse))
        
        plt.subplot(122)
        sns.scatterplot(x='y', y='resid', data=res).set_title("Residual plot")
        
        plt.show()
    
    return round(actual_rmse, 4)

Then I use gridsearch to find the best parameter alpha and gamma, the number of folds is set to 5, scoring method is negaive root mean sqaured error. I have tried different degree manually, and it shows degree 2 has the best performance to this data and has the best speed. The range of alpha and gamma are also tried out. tuning with a large number of parameters is time cost. so I use two groups of parameters and using the best parameters which is best for the validation data and test data.

In [19]:
def best_param(X_train, y_train, X_test, y_test):
    #parameter tuning with more alphas and less number gammas
    m_alpha = GridSearchCV(KernelRidge(kernel='poly', degree = 2),
                     param_grid={"alpha": np.logspace(-5, 1, num=10),
                                 "gamma": np.logspace(-5, 1, num=4)},
                     scoring = 'neg_root_mean_squared_error', cv=5).fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    #parameter tuning with more gammas and less alphas
    m_gamma = GridSearchCV(KernelRidge(kernel='poly', degree = 2),
                 param_grid={"alpha": np.logspace(-5, 1, num=4),
                             "gamma": np.logspace(-5, 1, num=10)},
                 scoring = 'neg_root_mean_squared_error', cv=5).fit(X_train, y_train)
    
    #test model
    rmse_alpha = model_fit(m_alpha, X_test, y_test, alpha = m_alpha.best_estimator_.alpha,
              gamma = m_alpha.best_estimator_.gamma, plot=False)
    
    rmse_gamma = model_fit(m_gamma, X_test, y_test, alpha = m_gamma.best_estimator_.alpha,
              gamma = m_gamma.best_estimator_.gamma, plot=False)
    
    if rmse_alpha < rmse_gamma:
        return m_alpha
    else:
        return m_gamma

4. Discussion¶

My final model is kernel ridge regression model with polynomial kernel of degree 2. This model will take the feature into higher demension, calculate the dual coeffient and then use dual coeffient and kernel feature to do prediction. The kernel feature consider the non-linear property of feature similarity which is better than only use linear feature in other models. It also account for the feature interaction. The data used for this model has both nemeric data and categorical data (only zero and one) and only numeric data are standard scaled. I also use log scale of sale_price and lot_area because they are right skewed and using log scale will make prediction better. below is my model performance for test data.

The polynomial kernel will increase the number of features, these feature is constructed by the original feature and has strong relationship to the original feature. The higher dual coeffient means more significant the corresponding kernel feature. This model is better than linear regression, so it is accurate and useful.

This model will take all the information provided except the year_sold and a new variable nb_level which means the price level of each neighborhood. The model is predicting the log sclae sale price, so before calculating the root mean squared error, I exponential it to the real scale.
